columns.colDescription: A unique identifier assigned to a poison pill record.
The date the poison pill was announced via a press release.
The date the company entered into the rights agreement with the rights agent. The rights agreement describes the terms and provisions of the poison pill.

In adopting the poison pill the company declares a dividend of a Right to be distributed to each shareholder of record on that date (Record Date) and the Rights attach to the outstanding common share on that date.

The date on which the current (or if no longer in force, most recent) poison pill was originally scheduled to expire and cease to exist. The plan's expiration date remains current and reflects any amendments to the plan to either accelerate or extend the plan.
A flag denoting if there is a sunset provision, which provides that the poison pill will lapse if not ratified in a pre-determined amount of years.
The specified number of years in which the poison pill will be reviewed and if not ratified or re-adopted it will lapse.

A Three Year Independent Director Evaluation is a mechanism whereby a committee of the board of directors comprised of independent directors meet not less than every three years to review the terms and conditions of the company's poison pill including whether the termination or modification of the poison pill is in the best interests of the company and shareholders.
The date on which the poison pill was terminated before expiration as a result of the pill being redeemed, the company being acquired, or having been removed in any other way.

The dollar amount rightholders will pay for the securities purchasable per right (i.e. 1/100 of a share of series A preferred stock) upon separation. In the event the rights flip-in or flip-over, holders will pay the exercise price to purchase common shares of the company or of the acquiring company.

The dollar amount rightholders will pay for the securities purchasable per right upon separation. This is the current exercise price as listed in the rights agreement or if applicable any amendment to the rights agreement. No adjustments are made to this price for any stock splits unless a formal amendment was made by the company to take into account the effects of the split.
The exercise price of the poison pill at the time the pill was adopted.
The code that represents the currency of the exercise price data.
The closing stock price of the company on the day the poison pill was adopted. This stock price is not adjusted for subsequent stock splits.
The closing stock price of the company on the day before the poison pill was adopted. This stock price is not adjusted for subsequent stock splits.
A textual description of in play details.

A flag denoting if there is a provision where right holders have the option to pay the exercise price in cash or in common shares. In some cases the alternative to pay the exercise price in common shares is at the discretion of the board of directors. This alternative allows stockholders with lesser financial means to take full economic advantage of the Rights.

The type of security purchasable per right upon the rights separating from the common shares and becoming exercisable for the exercise price. Each right typically allows the holder to purchase common stock or a fraction of a share of a special series of preferred stock designed to be the economic equivalent of 1 common share.

The number of shares purchasable per right upon the rights separating from the common shares and becoming exercisable for the exercise price. Each right typically allows the holder to purchase common stock or a fraction of a share of a special series of preferred stock designed to be the economic equivalent of 1 common share.

A description of the securities purchasable per right upon the rights separating from the common shares and becoming exercisable for the exercise price. The securities purchasable per right are typically 1 share of common stock or a fraction of a share of a special series of preferred stock designed to be the economic equivalent of 1 common share.
The percentage of beneficial ownership at which the rights separate from the common shares.

The number of days following a public announcement that a person or group has become the beneficial owner of a specified percentage of ownership (Percent to Separate Person) that the rights will become exercisable and detach from the common shares.
The percentage of beneficial ownership resulting from a tender offer at which the rights separate from the common shares.

The number of days following the commencement of, or announcement to make a tender offer or exchange offer which would result in a person owning a specified percent of the company (Percent to Separate Tender Offer) on which the rights will detach from the common shares and become exercisable.

A flag denoting if there is a provision where the rights flip-in and allow all holders except the acquiring person to purchase additional common shares at a discount as a result of an acquiring person engineering a reclassification of securities or recapitalization/reorganization of the company which results in the acquiring person's proportionate ownership interest to be increased more than 1percent.

A White Squire trigger exception gives the board the flexibility to make a person exempt from the provisions of the poison pill at its discretion in order to allow the person to increase its stake beyond the threshold that would otherwise set the rights plan in motion (Acquiring Person Percent).

Provision whereby if the board determines in good faith that a person who surpassed the ownership level that triggers the pill crossed the threshold inadvertently and has no intention of changing or influencing control of the company and the person promptly divests a sufficient number of shares to go under the trigger, the poison pill will not be activated.
A flag denoting if there is a grandfather provision which a named shareholder or a certain type of shareholder is exempted from triggering the poison pill within certain limitations.
A discount to market price holders of outstanding rights will receive in the event the rights flip-in.
The percentage at which the rights "flip-over" and allow all holders to purchase shares of the acquiring company (or surviving company in the merger) at a discount (usually 50percent).

A flag denoting if there is an Adverse Person provision which allows the Rights to separate and become exercisable and a flip-in to occur at a lesser percentage (typically 10percent) of ownership in the event the board deems a shareholder to be an 'Adverse Person'.

The minimum percentage of beneficial ownership at which the company can deem a person to be an 'Adverse Person'. An Adverse Person provision allows the Rights to separate and become exercisable and a flip-in to occur at a lesser percentage (typically 10percent) of ownership in the event the board deems a shareholder to be an Adverse Person.

A flag denoting if there is a provision whereby the rights flip-in and allow all holders except the acquiring person to purchase additional common shares of the company at a discount (usually 50percent) as a result of an acquiring person engaging in self-dealing transactions.

The percentage of beneficial ownership at which the rights flip-in and allow all holders except the acquiring person to purchase additional common shares of the company at a discount (usually 50percent) as a result of a shareholder engaging in self-dealing transactions.

A flag denoting if there is a provision whereby the rights "flip-in" and allow all holders except the acquiring person to purchase additional common shares of the company at a discount as a result of an acquiring person engineering a reclassification of securities or recapitalization/reorganization of the company, resulting in the acquiring person's ownership interest to increase more than 1percent.

The percentage of beneficial ownership at which the rights flip-in and allow all holders except the acquiring person to purchase additional common shares at a discount as a result of a shareholder engineering a reclassification of securitiesor recapitalization/ reorganization of the company which results in the acquiring person's proportionate ownership interest being increased by more than 1percent.
A flag denoting if the poison pill includes a provision whereby the application of the poison pill will not apply to offers for the company that meets predefined criteria.

A textual description of the permitted bid provision. The text is taken from the rights agreement on what criteria is needed for an offer to qualify as a Permitted Offer. A Permitted Offer provision provides that the application of the poison pill will not apply to offers for the company that meets predefined criteria.

A flag denoting if there is an adopted provision whereby at the request of the acquirer a referendum is called where stockholders vote on the takeover offer and if approved the poison pill is redeemed.

A flag denoting if the poison pill is chewable. Chewable poison pills provide that certain types of qualified offers, regardless of whether approved by the board, require the pill to be redeemed, either automatically or by a stockholder vote.

A flag denoting if the poison pill includes a provision in the amendment section of the rights agreement that provides that the board can reduce the trigger thresholds of the poison pill to as low as a specified percentage (usually 10 percent) at any time prior to a person acquiring a percent of company stock equal to the lowered threshold.

The percentage the board may lower the trigger threshold to if the poison pill includes a provision in the amendment section of the rights agreement that provides that the board can reduce the trigger thresholds of the poison pill to as low as a specified percentage (usually 10 percent) at any time prior to a person acquiring a percent of company stock equal to the lowered threshold.
A flag denoting if the poison pill includes a provision whereby the right to amend the poison pill is specifically reserved for 'Continuing', 'Disinterested', or 'Independent' directors only.
The dollar amount per right the company will pay each holder of a right to redeem (cancel before the expiration date) the outstanding rights. The redemption price is typically one cent ($.01).

The Redemption Window is the number of days following the time that the trigger threshold has been passed that the company may redeem the rights. Upon the board of directors electing to redeem the rights, the right to exercise the rights terminate and the holder of the right will receive the redemption price.

A flag denoting if there is a provision whereby after the redemption window has expired the company's right to redeem the outstanding rights will be reinstated in order to allow for a merger with a white knight.

A flag denoting if there is a provision whereby after the redemption window has expired the company's right to redeem the outstanding rights will be reinstated if the Acquiring Person reduces its ownership below a set a percentage (typically 10percent). This provision is sometimes referred to as a 'yo-yo' or 'springing right of redemption'.
The percentage of ownership that an Acquiring Person must go below in order for the company's right to redeem the outstanding rights to be reinstated after the Redemption Window has expired.

A flag denoting if the poison pill includes a deferred redemption provision, which is a common strategy to facilitate a hostile acquisition of a company with a poison pill is to launch a proxy fight to replace the board with a slate of directors who would redeem the pill.
The number of days a newly elected board is prohibited from redeeming a poison pill under the deferred redemption provision.

A flag denoting if there is an Exchange Feature, which provides the board of directors the alternative to exchange all or some of the outstanding and exercisable rights, except those held by the acquiring person, for securities (usually 1 share of common stock) after the rights have been triggered.
A flag denoting if the poison pill was adopted by a company that was 'in play'. The majority of poison pills are adopted as a routine measure and not against a specific takeover threat.

A flag denoting if there is a provision that provides a newly elected board the right to redeem the poison pill, including to facilitate an unsolicited acquisition, but only if certain Value Enhancement procedures are followed.

A flag denoting if the poison pill was put to a shareholder vote. Shareholder approval is not required to adopt a poison pill in the U.S. but companies have increasingly been submitting poison pill adoptions/amendments up to a shareholder vote. This item includes current poison pills where the adoption, an amendment, or the continuation of the pill was submitted for shareholder approval.
